## Recommended: Adopt `System.IO.Abstractions`

This is a battle-tested NuGet package that wraps the entire `System.IO` surface behind injectable interfaces — no need to write custom wrappers.

**1. Install the package:**
```
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
```

**2. Register in DI:**
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

**3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes:**
```csharp
public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Read(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Write(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool DirectoryExists(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

**4. Test with `MockFileSystem`:**
```
dotnet add <TestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```
```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});
mockFs.Directory.CreateDirectory("/data");

var sut = new MyService(mockFs);

sut.Write("/data/out.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/data/out.txt"));
Assert.True(sut.DirectoryExists("/data"));
```

---

**Why this over a custom wrapper?**
- Covers `File`, `Directory`, `Path`, `FileInfo`, etc. — you won't need another wrapper later.
- `MockFileSystem` gives you an in-memory filesystem out of the box — no mocking framework needed.
- Stateless, so register as `AddSingleton`.

Once installed, use the `migrate-static-to-wrapper` skill (or do it manually) to replace existing `File.*` / `Directory.*` call sites with the injected `IFileSystem`.
